.SS "0.23 2026\-07\-08 \s-1CDT\s0"
.IX Subsection "0.23 2026-07-08 CDT"
\&\f(CW\*(C`rename_cols\*(C'\fR takes HoH as input
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`write_table\*(C'\fR prints row names as first column; writes longtable with comments
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`assign\*(C'\fR gains \f(CW\*(C`map_cell { ... }\*(C'\fR for in-place per-cell column edits
.PP
\fIassign\fR
.IX Subsection "assign"
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`assign\*(C'\fR now accepts a third kind of column value, \f(CW\*(C`map_cell { ... }\*(C'\fR, for editing an existing column in place — no \*(L"copy, substitute, return\*(R" boilerplate and no dependence on \f(CW\*(C`s///r\*(C'\fR (unavailable on the older perls this module supports).
.IP "\(bu" 4
Inside a \f(CW\*(C`map_cell\*(C'\fR block, \f(CW$_\fR is the \fBnamed column's current cell\fR (not the whole row), the block's return value is \fBignored\fR, and the modified \f(CW$_\fR is stored back: \f(CW\*(C`assign($df, \*(AqRes.\*(Aq => map_cell { s/^[A\-Z]:// })\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
The row is still available as \f(CW$_[0]\fR (sibling columns), the index as \f(CW$_[1]\fR, and the row key as \f(CW$_[2]\fR (HoH only).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBUndef/missing cells pass through untouched\fR (undef in → undef out): the block is skipped for them, so \f(CW\*(C`s///\*(C'\fR never warns on an uninitialized value.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Supported on all three shapes; for HoA the target column must already exist. A plain \f(CW\*(C`sub { ... }\*(C'\fR is unchanged, so \f(CW\*(C`map_cell\*(C'\fR is purely additive.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`map_cell\*(C'\fR is exported alongside \f(CW\*(C`assign\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Tests: \f(CW\*(C`assign.t\*(C'\fR (AoH + HoA) and \f(CW\*(C`assign.HoH.t\*(C'\fR gained \f(CW\*(C`map_cell\*(C'\fR coverage — in-place \f(CW\*(C`s///\*(C'\fR, \f(CW$_[0]\fR/\f(CW$_[1]\fR/\f(CW$_[2]\fR context, new-column-from-undef, the missing-HoA-column death path, and \f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR guards. Verified building and passing the full suite on perl 5.10.1, 5.12.5 (long-double), and 5.42.2.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`group_by\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "group_by"
.PP
Fixed group_by to honor all filter hashrefs (option 1)
.PP
Root cause: the \s-1XS\s0 captured only \s-1\fIST\s0\fR\|(3), so every filter hashref after the first was silently dropped — including the \s-1README\s0's documented multi-hashref form.
.PP
Change (LikeR.xs):
\&\- Removed the \fIsingle\-ST\fR\|(3) capture and the filter_hv \s-1PREINIT\s0 var.
\&\- Added a \s-1FOR_EACH_FILTER\s0(body) macro that walks the arg stack from \s-1\fIST\s0\fR\|(3) to \s-1ST\s0(items\-1), iterating every { column => sub } pair and ANDing them together. It iterates the stack directly rather than heap-collecting the hashrefs, so a croaking filter sub still can't leak anything (verified). Non-hashref args are skipped.
\&\- Rewrote the filter loop in all three branches (AoH / HoA / HoH) to use the macro, keeping each branch's own value-fetch logic.
.PP
One build wrinkle worth noting: xsubpp parses every non\-# line in the inter-XSUB region as a candidate function signature, so a /* ... */ comment there breaks the build (it tried to parse column => sub / (\s-1\fIST\s0\fR\|(3)..) as a signature). I moved the macro's documentation into the \s-1XSUB\s0 body (real C) and left the macro comment-free, matching the existing \s-1EVAL_FILTER\s0 style.
.PP
Tests (t/group_by.HoH.filter.t, 17 assertions):
\&\- HoH single-column filter, \s-1AND\s0 filter (both the one-hashref and separate-hashref forms now give identical results), no-match → empty hash, missing/undef target excluded despite passing the filter, and no_leaks_ok
.PP
Mentioning a non-existent column is now fatal.
