\fI\f(CI\*(C`assign\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "assign"
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`assign\*(C'\fR now accepts two kinds of column value, so a function that already returns a whole column (like \f(CW\*(C`rank\*(C'\fR) drops in without wrapping.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBPer-row coderef\fR (unchanged): called once per row, \f(CW$_\fR is the row, and the single scalar it returns is the cell. A single arrayref return is still stored \fIas the cell\fR, so arrayref-valued columns keep working.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBWhole-column coderef\fR (new): if the coderef returns a \fIlist\fR of more than one value, that whole list becomes the column, laid down positionally. This is what makes \f(CW\*(C`\*(AqΔG rank\*(Aq => sub { rank( vals($df, \*(AqdG_kcal_mol\*(Aq) ) }\*(C'\fR work directly — no \f(CW\*(C`[ ... ]\*(C'\fR needed.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBArrayref value\fR (new): a ready-made column, e.g. \f(CW\*(C`col => [ rank(...) ]\*(C'\fR, copied into the frame.
.PP
The coderef is probed once (row 0 for AoH/HoH, the first synthesized view for HoA) to decide per-row vs whole-column, so per-row code is never run twice on row 0. Every column value is length-checked against the row count and a mismatch dies. \fBHoH\fR is now a supported, documented shape alongside AoH and HoA; whole-column and arrayref values align to \fBsorted key order\fR.
.PP
Tests: \f(CW\*(C`assign.t\*(C'\fR (AoH + HoA) and \f(CW\*(C`assign_HoH.t\*(C'\fR were expanded to cover every shape × value-kind combination — per-row scalar, whole-column list, arrayref value, single-arrayref-as-cell, \f(CW\*(C`rank()\*(C'\fR integration, chaining, \f(CW$_[1]\fR index, \f(CW$_[2]\fR row key (HoH), overwrite, ragged HoA columns, empty frames, length-mismatch and bad-value / odd-arg / non-hash-row death paths, and \f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR guards on the new whole-column and arrayref paths.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "read_table"
.PP
Fixed handling of commented-out header lines and made filter columns
referenceable by the name as it appears in the file.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBCommented-out header recovery.\fR \f(CW\*(C`_parse_csv_file\*(C'\fR treats a line whose
comment marker is followed by whitespace (e.g. \f(CW\*(C`# PDB<TAB>score\*(C'\fR) as a
comment and drops it, so a header written that way never reached the
callback and the first \fIdata\fR row was silently mistaken for the header.
\&\f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR now recovers it: the first physical line, if it is
\&\f(CW\*(C`marker + whitespace\*(C'\fR and splits into two or more fields, is held as a
candidate header and confirmed only when its field count matches the first
data row. If the counts disagree the candidate was an ordinary leading
comment and is discarded, so a prose comment that happens to contain the
separator (e.g. \f(CW\*(C`# note, see README\*(C'\fR) is never mistaken for a header. A
marker hugging its text (\f(CW\*(C`#id,val\*(C'\fR) is delivered by the parser and
un-commented in the callback as before. The marker and any following
whitespace are stripped, so \f(CW\*(C`# PDB\*(C'\fR is stored as the clean name \f(CW\*(C`PDB\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBFilter columns may be named as written in the file.\fR Filter keys are
matched against the header by exact name first, then retried with the
leading comment marker (and surrounding whitespace) stripped, so a
commented-header column resolves whether it is referenced as \f(CW\*(C`# PDB\*(C'\fR or by
its clean name \f(CW\*(C`PDB\*(C'\fR:
.Sp
.Vb 4
\& read_table(
\&     \*(Aqregression_rank.tabular.tsv\*(Aq,
\&     filter => { \*(Aq# PDB\*(Aq => sub { $_ == 2 } },
\& );
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBClearer \*(L"column not found\*(R" error.\fR The failure now names the file and
lists the actual header instead of printing it to \s-1STDOUT\s0 (a library
shouldn't print):
.Sp
.Vb 2
\& read_table: Filter column \*(Aqnope\*(Aq not found in the header of FILE;
\& header is: \*(AqPDB\*(Aq, \*(Aqscore\*(Aq
.Ve
.SS "0.20"
.IX Subsection "0.20"
addition of \f(CW\*(C`ncol\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`nrow\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`pnorm\*(C'\fR functions
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`filter\*(C'\fR can filter by row names with \f(CW$_[1]\fR
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`view\*(C'\fR now accepts array of arrays in addition to AoH, HoA, and HoH
.PP
\fIcsort\fR
.IX Subsection "csort"
.PP
Two behavioural changes, both contained to the \f(CW\*(C`csort\*(C'\fR \s-1XSUB\s0 (the \f(CW\*(C`cs_*\*(C'\fR helpers are untouched).
.PP
\&\fBRow names survive a Hash-of-Hashes sort.\fR Sorting a HoH previously discarded the outer keys. Now each row is folded into a \fIfresh\fR row hash (a private container over aliased, read-only cells) that carries its outer key under a \f(CW\*(C`row.name\*(C'\fR column, so the name flows into whichever shape you request:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& my $hoh = { alpha => { id => 1 }, beta => { id => 2 } };
\& 
\& csort($hoh, \*(Aqid\*(Aq);          # AoH: each row gains a row.name field
\& csort($hoh, \*(Aqid\*(Aq, \*(Aqhoa\*(Aq);   # HoA: an aligned row.name column
.Ve
.IP "\(bu" 4
The column name defaults to \f(CW\*(C`row.name\*(C'\fR and can be overridden with an optional 4th argument (mirroring \f(CW\*(C`hoa2hoh\*(C'\fR's named-key style): \f(CW\*(C`csort($df, \*(Aqid\*(Aq, \*(Aqaoh\*(Aq, \*(Aqsample\*(Aq)\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
The outer key is authoritative — it wins over any pre-existing same-named field in the row.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Once present, the column is sortable like any other: \f(CW\*(C`csort($hoh, \*(Aqrow.name\*(Aq)\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Because rows are now \fIcopied\fR rather than shared, the caller's HoH is never mutated by the injection. (Minor behaviour change: output rows are no longer the same refs as the source rows.)
.PP
\&\fBClearer usage message.\fR The signature is now \f(CW\*(C`csort(...)\*(C'\fR, so xsubpp no longer emits the misleading auto-generated \f(CW\*(C`Usage: Stats::LikeR::csort(data, by, output=&PL_sv_undef)\*(C'\fR. Argument count is checked by hand, and the croak now shows both real calling forms:
.PP
.Vb 3
\& Usage: csort($df, \*(Aqcolumn.name\*(Aq, \*(AqHoA\*(Aq)
\&    or  csort($df, sub { $b\->{\*(AqNo.\*(Aq} <=> $a\->{\*(AqNo.\*(Aq} }, \*(Aqhoa\*(Aq)
\&   (optional 4th arg names the row\-name column when sorting a HoH; default \*(Aqrow.name\*(Aq)
.Ve
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`data\*(C'\fR/\f(CW\*(C`by\*(C'\fR/\f(CW\*(C`output\*(C'\fR are read as \f(CW\*(C`ST(0..2)\*(C'\fR; \f(CW\*(C`output\*(C'\fR still defaults to matching the input shape.
.PP
\&\fBTightened validation messages.\fR The \f(CW$data\fR croak now reads \f(CW\*(C`hash\-ref (HoA or HoH)\*(C'\fR, and the \f(CW$by\fR croak includes a concrete example: \f(CW\*(C`a column name (e.g. \*(AqNo.\*(Aq) or a comparator code\-ref using $a and $b, e.g. sub { $b\->{\*(AqNo.\*(Aq} <=> $a\->{\*(AqNo.\*(Aq} }\*(C'\fR. Existing HoA croaks (\f(CW\*(C`unequal lengths\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`not found\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`not an array\-ref\*(C'\fR) are unchanged.
.PP
When sorting, undefined values in the sorting column are placed at the bottom
.PP
\fIcor\fR
.IX Subsection "cor"
.PP
Fixed an unsigned-integer underflow in \f(CW\*(C`kendall_tau_b\*(C'\fR and added a regression test.
.PP
Bug
.IX Subsection "Bug"
.PP
In \f(CW\*(C`kendall_tau_b\*(C'\fR, concordant/discordant counts \f(CW\*(C`C\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`D\*(C'\fR are declared \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR (unsigned). The numerator was computed as:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& return (NV)(C \- D) / denom;
.Ve
.PP
The subtraction \f(CW\*(C`C \- D\*(C'\fR happens in unsigned arithmetic \fIbefore\fR the cast to \f(CW\*(C`NV\*(C'\fR. When discordant pairs dominate (\f(CW\*(C`D > C\*(C'\fR), the result wraps to a huge positive value instead of going negative.
.PP
For the arrays:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& dG_kcal_mol:  \-7.765, \-9.328, \-10.326, \-9.038, \-9.608, \-9.779, \-9.975, \-6.906
\& anomaly_rank: 154, 155, 161, 188, 76, 172, 173, 69
.Ve
.PP
there are \f(CW\*(C`C = 9\*(C'\fR concordant and \f(CW\*(C`D = 19\*(C'\fR discordant pairs (no ties). \f(CW\*(C`9 \- 19\*(C'\fR wraps to \f(CW18446744073709551607\fR, so the function returned ~\f(CW6.6e17\fR instead of the correct \f(CW\*(C`\-10/28 = \-0.3571428571\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Fix
.IX Subsection "Fix"
.PP
Cast each operand to \f(CW\*(C`NV\*(C'\fR before subtracting, so the arithmetic is signed:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& return ((NV)C \- (NV)D) / denom;
.Ve
.PP
Only that one line changed. The denominator sums (\f(CW\*(C`C + D + tie_x\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`C + D + tie_y\*(C'\fR) are non-negative, so they were left as-is.
.PP
Regression test — \f(CW\*(C`cor.t\*(C'\fR
.IX Subsection "Regression test — cor.t"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Kendall on the offending arrays pinned to \f(CW\*(C`\-0.3571428571\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Explicit \f(CW\*(C`[\-1, 1]\*(C'\fR range guard (the real backstop — the pre-fix value \f(CW\*(C`~6.6e17\*(C'\fR blows past the bound regardless of exact magnitude), plus a negative-sign assertion.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Pearson (\f(CW\*(C`\-0.4889102301\*(C'\fR), Spearman (\f(CW\*(C`\-0.4761904762\*(C'\fR), and default-method coverage of the three \f(CW\*(C`compute_cor\*(C'\fR branches.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Kendall boundary cases: perfectly concordant (\f(CW+1\fR), perfectly discordant (\f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR), self-correlation (\f(CW+1\fR), and a tie case exercising \f(CW\*(C`tie_x\*(C'\fR in the denominator.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR per method (guarded with \f(CW\*(C`unless $INC{\*(AqDevel/Cover.pm\*(Aq}\*(C'\fR).
.IP "\(bu" 4
Croak paths: length mismatch, unknown method, zero-variance input.
.PP
\fI\s-1XS\s0 refactor\fR
.IX Subsection "XS refactor"
.PP
Consolidate helper functions to reduce binary size, find bugs, and back the changes with tests. Every change was validated by translating the \s-1XS\s0 (\f(CW\*(C`ExtUtils::ParseXS\*(C'\fR) and compiling the result
with the module's own \f(CW\*(C`ccflags\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Outcome
.IX Subsection "Outcome"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBNet change to the source:\fR ~154 fewer lines; helper-function count down by 4 (7 removed, 3 added).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBGenuine bugs fixed:\fR two instances of the same latent defect (see below). The rest of the work was behavior-preserving consolidation.
.PP
Function consolidation
.IX Subsection "Function consolidation"
.PP
All merges were confirmed behavior-preserving: the collapsed comparators are
equivalent on ordinary values, \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR, and infinities, and \f(CW\*(C`compute_ranks\*(C'\fR and
\&\f(CW\*(C`rank_data\*(C'\fR produce identical average ranks.
.PP
Bugs
.IX Subsection "Bugs"
.PP
Two comparators stabilized their sort by returning \f(CW\*(C`a\->idx \- b\->idx\*(C'\fR directly,
where the index field is an unsigned \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR. The subtraction wraps and is then
truncated to \f(CW\*(C`int\*(C'\fR, which is implementation-defined and gives the wrong sign
once a difference exceeds \f(CW\*(C`INT_MAX\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`compare_index\*(C'\fR — removed entirely (the routine that used it, \f(CW\*(C`compute_ranks\*(C'\fR, was replaced by \f(CW\*(C`rank_data\*(C'\fR).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`cmp_pval\*(C'\fR — the tie-break comparator in the p\-adjust path. \fBMissed in the initial review; found later\fR via a \f(CW\*(C`\-Wconversion\*(C'\fR compile of the earlier source. Fixed to compare with the \f(CW\*(C`(a > b) \- (a < b)\*(C'\fR idiom.
.PP
\&\fBCaveat on severity:\fR on every mainstream \s-1ABI\s0 (\s-1LP64\s0, \s-1LLP64\s0, \s-1ILP32\s0), the
low-word truncation happens to reproduce the correct sign for any array smaller
than ~2^31 elements, so this never produces a wrong result at realistic sizes.
It is a portability/UB issue, not a runtime failure, which is why no functional
test detects it (see \*(L"Testing\*(R", below).
.PP
.Vb 1
\& C<LikeR.xs> — consolidated helpers; C<compare_index> removed; C<cmp_pval> fixed.
.Ve
.PP
