\fI\f(CI\*(C`aov\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "aov"
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fB underflow on empty arrays.\fR Three loops were bounded by \f(CW\*(C`av_len(...)\*(C'\fR
compared against an unsigned counter; \f(CW\*(C`av_len\*(C'\fR returns \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR for an empty array,
which turned \f(CW\*(C`k <= len\*(C'\fR into a \f(CW\*(C`SIZE_MAX\*(C'\fR loop. The \f(CW\*(C`stack()\*(C'\fR value loop, the \f(CW\*(C`.\*(C'\fR
column-expansion loop, and the \f(CW\*(C`group_stats\*(C'\fR column loop now use a signed
\&\f(CW\*(C`SSize_t\*(C'\fR bound.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBHoH row count.\fR Row count for hash-of-hashes input was taken from the return
value of \f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR; it now uses \f(CW\*(C`HvUSEDKEYS(hv)\*(C'\fR with a separate
\&\f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR, matching \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBBuffer overflow in interaction parsing.\fR \f(CW\*(C`strcpy(right, colon + 1)\*(C'\fR into a
fixed \f(CW\*(C`char right[256]\*(C'\fR is now \f(CW\*(C`snprintf(right, sizeof(right), ...)\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Performance / memory
.IX Subsection "Performance / memory"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBRemoved the per-row \f(CB\*(C`row_x\*(C'\fB scratch allocation.\fR Design rows are built
directly into \f(CW\*(C`X_mat[valid_n]\*(C'\fR; \f(CW\*(C`valid_n\*(C'\fR simply does not advance on a rejected
row. Interaction columns read their operands from the same in-progress row, so
the logic is unchanged.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`row_names\*(C'\fB is no longer dead.\fR Surviving row names are transferred (pointer
move, no copy) into \f(CW\*(C`surv_names\*(C'\fR to key \f(CW\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fR; rejected rows are freed
in place.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBDropped a \f(CB\*(C`restrict\*(C'\fB \s-1UB\s0.\fR \f(CW\*(C`orig_data_sv\*(C'\fR aliases \f(CW\*(C`data_sv\*(C'\fR; the \f(CW\*(C`restrict\*(C'\fR
qualifier was removed.
.PP
New, \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR\-compatible output keys
.IX Subsection "New, predict-compatible output keys"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`coefficients\*(C'\fB\fR — \s-1OLS\s0 estimates recovered by back-substitution on the R factor
left in \f(CW\*(C`X_mat\*(C'\fR against Q'y in \f(CW\*(C`Y\*(C'\fR (no re-derivation). Keys are the expanded term
names (\f(CW\*(C`Intercept\*(C'\fR, continuous names, \f(CW\*(C`base.level\*(C'\fR dummies, and \f(CW\*(C`a:b\*(C'\fR interaction
products). Aliased columns are reported as \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR, which \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR drops.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fB\fR — \f(CW\*(C`Xb\*(C'\fR over the non-aliased columns, keyed by surviving row
name. Computed from a snapshot of the design (\f(CW\*(C`Dsav\*(C'\fR) taken before the \s-1QR\s0
overwrites \f(CW\*(C`X_mat\*(C'\fR. Costs one transient copy of the design matrix; negligible for
typical \s-1ANOVA\s0 where the column count is small.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`xlevels\*(C'\fB\fR — sorted level list per factor, index 0 = reference, aligned with
the contrast coding used to build the dummies.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`family\*(C'\fB\fR — \f(CW"gaussian"\fR.
.PP
Cleanup-path correctness
.IX Subsection "Cleanup-path correctness"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`xlevels_hv\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`Dsav\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`surv_names\*(C'\fR are freed on both the \*(L"0 degrees of
freedom\*(R" croak and the normal exit. The interaction-main-effects croak in
\&\s-1PHASE\s0 3 also frees \f(CW\*(C`xlevels_hv\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Known limitations (unchanged)
.IX Subsection "Known limitations (unchanged)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
The intercept-stripping string surgery (\f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR, \f(CW+0\fR, \f(CW+1\fR, ...) operates on the
whole \s-1RHS\s0 and can still mangle \f(CW\*(C`I(x\-1)\*(C'\fR\-style transforms; treat \f(CW\*(C`I()\*(C'\fR with
arithmetic constants carefully.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Top-level keys \f(CW\*(C`coefficients\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`fitted.values\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`xlevels\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`family\*(C'\fR /
\&\f(CW\*(C`group_stats\*(C'\fR share the return hash with the \s-1ANOVA\s0 rows; a predictor literally
named one of those would collide.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`predict\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "predict"
.PP
New: factor-bearing interaction terms
.IX Subsection "New: factor-bearing interaction terms"
.PP
Previously, interaction coefficients such as \f(CW\*(C`GroupB:Sexmale\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`GroupB:x\*(C'\fR fell
through to the continuous \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR path and died on a nonexistent column.
They are now handled directly:
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`dummy_hv\*(C'\fB\fR stores each dummy's factor base index (an \f(CW\*(C`IV\*(C'\fR) instead of
\&\f(CW&PL_sv_yes\fR, so a dummy name maps back to its \f(CW\*(C`(base, level)\*(C'\fR in O(1)
(\f(CW\*(C`level == name + strlen(base)\*(C'\fR). \f(CW\*(C`hv_exists\*(C'\fR lookups are unaffected.
.IP "\(bu" 4
During coefficient caching, any \f(CW\*(C`:\*(C'\fR term with at least one factor-dummy component
is routed to a separate list (\f(CW\*(C`icopy\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`ibeta\*(C'\fR); pure-continuous interactions
(e.g. \f(CW\*(C`x:z\*(C'\fR) stay on the existing \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR path, so prior behavior is
preserved.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Each routed term is parsed once into flat component arrays. Factor components
store a base index and level pointer; continuous components store the term string
and get the same up-front column-existence validation as main terms.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Per row, each factor's raw level is read once into \f(CW\*(C`raw_lv[]\*(C'\fR and reused by both
main effects and interactions (no duplicate \f(CW\*(C`get_data_string_alloc\*(C'\fR). An
interaction's value is the product of its components: a factor component
contributes \f(CW1.0\fR iff the row's level matches the dummy's level (reference levels
give \f(CW0\fR), continuous components go through \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR.
.PP
This covers factor×factor, factor×continuous, continuous×continuous, and n\-way
combinations.
.PP
Other
.IX Subsection "Other"
.IP "\(bu" 4
HoH row count uses \f(CW\*(C`HvUSEDKEYS\*(C'\fR (already present).
.IP "\(bu" 4
The unseen-factor-level croak now frees every level string already read for the
current row, not just the current one.
.PP
\fITests\fR
.IX Subsection "Tests"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`aov.t\*(C'\fB\fR — one-way \s-1ANOVA\s0 against hand-computed values (Df / Sum Sq / Mean Sq /
F / decomposition); identical results across HoA / HoH / AoH / stacked input;
simple regression; \f(CW\*(C`.\*(C'\fR expansion; intercept removal (\f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR); two-way with
interaction (Type I \s-1SS\s0 on a balanced design); NaN listwise deletion; all croak
paths; leak checks.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`predict.t\*(C'\fB\fR — \f(CW\*(C`predict(training) == fitted.values\*(C'\fR round-trips for one-way,
regression, factor×factor, factor×continuous, and continuous×continuous models;
explicit predicted values; agreement across HoA / AoH / HoH / flat newdata;
no-newdata path; binomial \f(CW\*(C`link\*(C'\fR vs \f(CW\*(C`response\*(C'\fR; gaussian identity link; all croak
paths; leak checks.
.PP
Leak tests use \f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR guarded by \f(CW\*(C`unless $INC{\*(AqDevel/Cover.pm\*(Aq}\*(C'\fR and skipped
when \f(CW\*(C`Test::LeakTrace\*(C'\fR is absent.
.PP
Assumptions worth confirming
.IX Subsection "Assumptions worth confirming"
.IP "\(bu" 4
The NaN-deletion test relies on \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term\*(C'\fR returning \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR for a non-finite
response value (an \f(CW\*(C`Inf \- Inf\*(C'\fR NaN is fed in deterministically).
.IP "\(bu" 4
The continuous×continuous round-trip relies on \f(CW\*(C`evaluate_term("x:z")\*(C'\fR yielding
\&\f(CW\*(C`x * z\*(C'\fR — the same assumption the pre-existing \f(CW\*(C`predict\*(C'\fR continuous-interaction
path already made. If that path was untested, this round-trip now exercises it.
.PP
