\fIfilter\fR
.IX Subsection "filter"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBAdded hash-of-hashes (HoH) input.\fR In addition to AoH and HoA, \f(CW\*(C`filter\*(C'\fR now accepts an HoH (\f(CW\*(C`{ key => { col => val, ... }, ... }\*(C'\fR); each inner hash is one row, and matching keys are preserved by default (HoH \-> HoH).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBAdded \f(CB\*(C`output.type\*(C'\fB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`filter($df, $pred, \*(Aqoutput.type\*(Aq => \*(Aqaoh\*(Aq|\*(Aqhoa\*(Aq)\*(C'\fR selects the returned shape (aliases \f(CW\*(C`out\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`output_type\*(C'\fR; a bare positional type also works). When omitted, the input shape is preserved. \f(CW\*(C`hoh\*(C'\fR is not a selectable output, since it would require choosing a key column.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`col()\*(C'\fB reworked, not removed.\fR Both predicate forms are kept: \f(CW\*(C`col(\*(Aqage\*(Aq) >= 18\*(C'\fR still works and is the concise/composable option, while a coderef covers everything else. Internally \f(CW\*(C`col()\*(C'\fR is now \fBpure Perl\fR — an overloaded class that builds a per-row closure — and \f(CW\*(C`filter\*(C'\fR unwraps that closure so \f(CW\*(C`col()\*(C'\fR and a coderef share one evaluation path. The previous standalone \s-1XS\s0 predicate evaluator (\f(CW\*(C`filt_eval\*(C'\fR/\f(CW\*(C`filt_ctx\*(C'\fR) is gone; delete it if your tree still has it. One consequence: a \f(CW\*(C`col()\*(C'\fR comparison now costs the same per row as the equivalent coderef (a Perl call), rather than being evaluated in C.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBUnchanged guarantees:\fR the input frame is never modified; \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR (and, for numeric ops, non-numeric) cells never match a \f(CW\*(C`col()\*(C'\fR comparison; AoH/HoH rows are shared rather than copied where possible; keep\-all/keep\-none shapes are well defined per output type; Perl 5.10 compatibility is retained. A latent \f(CW\*(C`SvTRUE(POPs)\*(C'\fR double-evaluation in the per-row call helper (which crashed on perls where \f(CW\*(C`SvTRUE\*(C'\fR is a multi-eval macro) was fixed along the way.
.PP
\fIread_table\fR
.IX Subsection "read_table"
.PP
Added an opt-in \f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR argument so \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR can read the file R
produces by default from \f(CW\*(C`write.table(x, sep="\et")\*(C'\fR.
.PP
The problem
.IX Subsection "The problem"
.PP
R's \f(CW\*(C`write.table\*(C'\fR defaults to \f(CW\*(C`row.names=TRUE, col.names=TRUE\*(C'\fR, which writes the
row-names column in every data row but emits \fBno header label for it\fR. So a
frame with N columns comes out as N header fields over N+1 data fields — e.g.
\&\f(CW\*(C`mtcars\*(C'\fR gives 11 headers but 12\-field rows. By default \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR (correctly)
rejects that as ragged:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& Alignment error on mtcars.tsv data row 1 (12 fields vs 11 headers).
.Ve
.PP
The change
.IX Subsection "The change"
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR turns on R's own \f(CW\*(C`read.table\*(C'\fR rule: \fBwhen, and only when, the
header is exactly one field short of the data rows, treat the first field of
each row as an (unlabelled) row-names column.\fR
.PP
.Vb 2
\& # default: the leading column is named \*(Aqrow_name\*(Aq
\& my $df = read_table(\*(Aqmtcars.tsv\*(Aq, \*(Aqauto.row.names\*(Aq => 1);
\& 
\& # or give it a name
\& my $df = read_table(\*(Aqmtcars.tsv\*(Aq, \*(Aqauto.row.names\*(Aq => \*(Aqmodel\*(Aq);
.Ve
.PP
The synthesized column behaves like any other first column: it appears in \f(CW\*(C`aoh\*(C'\fR
and \f(CW\*(C`hoa\*(C'\fR output, and for \f(CW\*(C`hoh\*(C'\fR it becomes the default key (so rows are keyed by
the model name). This also lines up with the existing handling of R's
\&\f(CW\*(C`col.names=NA\*(C'\fR output (a blank leading header), which still produces a
\&\f(CW\*(C`row_name\*(C'\fR column with no flag needed.
.PP
What did not change
.IX Subsection "What did not change"
.PP
The strict alignment check is still the default. Without \f(CW\*(C`auto.row.names\*(C'\fR the
lopsided file still croaks, and even with it, a row that is off by anything
other than exactly one field still croaks — so the corruption guard only relaxes
for the one case R itself treats specially.
.PP
Tested in \f(CW\*(C`t/read_table.2.t\*(C'\fR (16 assertions, Perl 5.10.1 and 5.38): aoh / hoa /
hoh output, custom column name, the already-aligned file (flag is a no-op), the
\&\f(CW\*(C`col.names=NA\*(C'\fR path, and the strict / ragged croak paths.
.PP
additional bugfix
