\fIBug fixes\fR
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.PP
\&\fBMemory leak on the zero-degrees-of-freedom error path.\fR When
\&\f(CW\*(C`valid_n <= p\*(C'\fR, the cleanup freed the \f(CW\*(C`valid_row_names\*(C'\fR \fIarray\fR but not the
per-row name strings it held (those had been transferred out of \f(CW\*(C`row_names\*(C'\fR,
whose own array was already freed). The strings leaked on every such error.
Added the per-entry \f(CW\*(C`Safefree\*(C'\fR loop before freeing the array, matching the
normal path.
.PP
\&\fBHoH input validated only the first row.\fR Only the first hash value was
checked to be a \f(CW\*(C`HASHREF\*(C'\fR; subsequent values were \f(CW\*(C`SvRV\*(C'\fR'd unconditionally, so
a malformed row (\f(CW\*(C`{ a => {...}, b => 5 }\*(C'\fR) dereferenced a non-reference. Every
row is now validated, with the partial allocations cleaned up before the
\&\f(CW\*(C`croak\*(C'\fR, mirroring the existing AoH path.
.PP
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`isspace\*(C'\fB on a possibly-signed \f(CB\*(C`char\*(C'\fB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`isspace(*src)\*(C'\fR is undefined for
byte values ≥ 0x80 on platforms where \f(CW\*(C`char\*(C'\fR is signed. Cast to
\&\f(CW\*(C`(unsigned char)\*(C'\fR before the call.
.PP
\fISpeed / \s-1RAM\s0 improvements\fR
.IX Subsection "Speed / RAM improvements"
.PP
\&\fBFormula buffer is now heap-allocated to fit.\fR \f(CW\*(C`char f_cpy[512]\*(C'\fR silently
truncated any longer formula. Replaced with a buffer sized to
\&\f(CW\*(C`strlen(formula) + 1\*(C'\fR, so there is no fixed limit and no truncation.
.PP
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`.\*(C'\fB\-expansion buffer is now a growable heap buffer.\fR \f(CW\*(C`char rhs_expanded[2048]\*(C'\fR
silently dropped expanded terms once full. It is now a buffer that doubles on
demand. Appends also went from \f(CW\*(C`strcat\*(C'\fR (which rescans from the start every
time — O(n²) over many columns) to an O(1) amortised append that tracks the
write position.
.PP
\&\fBNo more per-row scratch allocation in matrix construction.\fR The original
\&\f(CW\*(C`safemalloc\*(C'\fR'd a \f(CW\*(C`row_x\*(C'\fR buffer, filled it, copied it into \f(CW\*(C`X\*(C'\fR, and freed it
\&\fIfor every row\fR — \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR allocations plus \f(CW\*(C`n*p\*(C'\fR copies. Each candidate row is now
written straight into \f(CW\*(C`X\*(C'\fR at its prospective commit slot; a row that fails
listwise deletion is simply overwritten by the next candidate. This removes the
\&\f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR allocate/free cycles and the copy loop entirely.
.PP
\&\fBCategorical levels sorted with \f(CB\*(C`qsort\*(C'\fB.\fR The level list used an O(n²) bubble
sort; replaced with \f(CW\*(C`qsort\*(C'\fR (relevant only for high-cardinality factors).
.PP
\&\fBUnused tail of \f(CB\*(C`X\*(C'\fB reclaimed after listwise deletion.\fR \f(CW\*(C`X\*(C'\fR is allocated for
all \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR rows up front (\f(CW\*(C`valid_n\*(C'\fR is unknown until rows are scanned). When rows
are dropped, \f(CW\*(C`X\*(C'\fR is now \f(CW\*(C`Renew\*(C'\fRed down to \f(CW\*(C`valid_n * p\*(C'\fR, returning the unused
tail to the allocator before the \s-1OLS\s0 phase.
.PP
\&\fBMinor robustness.\fR The argument-parsing index was widened from
\&\f(CW\*(C`unsigned short\*(C'\fR to \f(CW\*(C`I32\*(C'\fR to match \f(CW\*(C`items\*(C'\fR, and the HoH row count now uses
\&\f(CW\*(C`HvUSEDKEYS\*(C'\fR rather than relying on \f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR's return value.
.PP
\fIKnown limitations (left unchanged)\fR
.IX Subsection "Known limitations (left unchanged)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
A multi-way term such as \f(CW\*(C`a*b*c\*(C'\fR is split only on the first \f(CW\*(C`*\*(C'\fR, so it yields
\&\f(CW\*(C`a\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`b*c\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`a:b*c\*(C'\fR rather than a full three-way expansion. Deeper
interactions silently fail (the unparsable term evaluates to \f(CW\*(C`NaN\*(C'\fR and the
rows are dropped). This matches the documented two-way \f(CW\*(C`*\*(C'\fR support.
.IP "\(bu" 4
HoA input takes the row count from the first column; columns shorter than
that simply contribute dropped rows rather than raising an error.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`oneway_test\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "oneway_test"
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.PP
\&\fBMemory leaks on error paths.\fR Nearly every \f(CW\*(C`croak\*(C'\fR after an allocation
leaked memory. \f(CW\*(C`croak\*(C'\fR does a \f(CW\*(C`longjmp\*(C'\fR, so anything allocated but not yet
freed is lost. Affected paths:
.IP "\(bu" 4
AoA and hash first-pass errors leaked \f(CW\*(C`sizes\*(C'\fR and any \f(CW\*(C`gnames[]\*(C'\fR entries
allocated so far.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Formula-mode \*(L"not found as an array ref\*(R" errors leaked \f(CW\*(C`lhs\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`rhs\*(C'\fR.
.PP
All post-allocation errors now route through a single \f(CW\*(C`fail:\*(C'\fR label that frees
every pointer unconditionally. Pointers are initialised to \f(CW\*(C`NULL\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`gnames\*(C'\fR
is zero-allocated with \f(CW\*(C`Newxz\*(C'\fR, so the cleanup is always safe to run.
.PP
\&\fBUndefined and non-numeric cells silently coerced to \f(CB0.0\fB.\fR The original
second pass used \f(CW\*(C`(svp && *svp) ? SvNV(*svp) : 0.0\*(C'\fR, meaning an \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR or
non-numeric cell was quietly treated as zero, silently corrupting the
F\-statistic. Each cell is now validated with \f(CW\*(C`SvOK\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`looks_like_number\*(C'\fR;
the call dies naming the group and observation index, consistent with the rest
of \f(CW\*(C`Stats::LikeR\*(C'\fR (\f(CW\*(C`mean\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`sum\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`cor\*(C'\fR, etc.).
.PP
\&\fBUnsigned wraparound on empty array input.\fR \f(CW\*(C`k = (size_t)av_len(in_av) + 1\*(C'\fR
cast to \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR \fIbefore\fR adding, so an empty array (\f(CW\*(C`av_len\*(C'\fR returns \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR)
produced \f(CW\*(C`SIZE_MAX\*(C'\fR rather than \f(CW0\fR. Changed to
\&\f(CW\*(C`k = (size_t)(av_len(in_av) + 1)\*(C'\fR so the \f(CW+1\fR is done in signed arithmetic
before the cast.
.PP
\&\fBUnreliable group count from \f(CB\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`hv_iterinit\*(C'\fR returns the
number of buckets in use rather than the number of keys for tied hashes.
Replaced with \f(CW\*(C`HvUSEDKEYS\*(C'\fR, which always returns the correct key count.
.PP
Improvements
.IX Subsection "Improvements"
.PP
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`var.equal\*(C'\fB accepted as an alias for \f(CB\*(C`var_equal\*(C'\fB.\fR R users write
\&\f(CW\*(C`var.equal\*(C'\fR; the argument parser now accepts both spellings.
.PP
\&\fBPerl memory \s-1API\s0 used throughout.\fR \f(CW\*(C`safemalloc\*(C'\fR and manual \f(CW\*(C`memcpy\*(C'\fR replaced
with \f(CW\*(C`Newx\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`Newxz\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`savepv\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`savepvn\*(C'\fR. \f(CW\*(C`savepvn\*(C'\fR additionally
preserves embedded \s-1NUL\s0 bytes in group key strings, which the previous
\&\f(CW\*(C`strlen\*(C'\fR\-based copies silently truncated.
.PP
Known limitations (not changed)
.IX Subsection "Known limitations (not changed)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
A factor column named \f(CW\*(C`Residuals\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`group_stats\*(C'\fR in a formula call will
collide with reserved top-level keys in the result hash.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Group names containing an embedded \s-1NUL\s0 are stored correctly but are still
truncated at \f(CW\*(C`strlen\*(C'\fR when written into the output hash keys.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`view\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "view"
.PP
default view shifted to 80 characters to match Linux window length
.PP
New features
.IX Subsection "New features"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`rows\*(C'\fB is accepted as a synonym for \f(CB\*(C`n\*(C'\fB\fR (the number of rows shown).
Passing both \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`rows\*(C'\fR is an error.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBUnknown arguments are now rejected.\fR \f(CW\*(C`view\*(C'\fR validates its argument names
against the documented set (\f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`rows\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`na\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`max_width\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`ellipsis\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`gap\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`cols\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`columns\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`to\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`return_only\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`row.names\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`row_names\*(C'\fR) and
dies listing any it does not recognise, so a misspelt option (e.g. \f(CW\*(C`widht\*(C'\fR)
is caught instead of silently ignored.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`n\*(C'\fB / \f(CB\*(C`rows\*(C'\fB is validated.\fR It must be a non-negative integer; \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR or
a non-numeric value now dies with a clear message instead of producing
warnings and being treated as \f(CW0\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBflat/simple hashes are accepted as input\fR
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`n => 0\*(C'\fB now still prints the column header.\fR Column names were collected
only from the rows being shown, so requesting zero rows produced an empty
header line. At least one row is now scanned (when data exists) so the
header always lists the columns.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBAn empty hash (\f(CB\*(C`{}\*(C'\fB) no longer dies.\fR It was rejected as
\&\fI\*(L"neither \s-1ARRAY\s0 nor \s-1HASH\s0\*(R"\fR; it is now shown as an empty table
(\f(CW\*(C`0 rows x 0 cols\*(C'\fR), matching the handling of an empty array.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBThe \f(CB\*(C`row_names\*(C'\fB alias now drives the Hash-of-Hashes label header.\fR The
header for the row-label column consulted only \f(CW\*(C`row.names\*(C'\fR, so
\&\f(CW\*(C`row_names => \*(Aqid\*(Aq\*(C'\fR displayed \f(CW\*(C`row_name\*(C'\fR instead of \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR. Both spellings are
now honoured consistently.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBMalformed nested values degrade gracefully.\fR A Hash-of-Arrays column or
Hash-of-Hashes row whose value is not actually an array/hash reference now
renders as empty cells rather than throwing a dereference error.
.PP
Performance
.IX Subsection "Performance"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Column gathering no longer sorts once per scanned row. Unique column names
are collected across the scanned rows and sorted a single time (same output
order), and the ellipsis length is computed once rather than per cell.
.PP
Tests
.IX Subsection "Tests"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`t/view.t\*(C'\fR is self-contained (the \f(CW\*(C`view\*(C'\fR implementation is inlined; it loads
no other files) and covers the new argument handling, the bug fixes above,
and the existing AoH / HoA / HoH behaviour, alignment, truncation, and
output-path handling.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`wilcox_test\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "wilcox_test"
.PP
Corrected four bugs in the \f(CW\*(C`wilcox_test\*(C'\fR \s-1XSUB\s0 plus a portability fix in its exact signed-rank helper. Behaviour on valid input is unchanged: the R\-agreement cases (unpaired \f(CW\*(C`W = 58\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`p = 0.13292\*(C'\fR; paired one-sided \f(CW\*(C`V = 40\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`p = 0.019531\*(C'\fR; separated exact \f(CW\*(C`W = 0\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`p = 0.028571\*(C'\fR) all still match R's \f(CW\*(C`wilcox.test\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBInvalid \f(CB\*(C`alternative\*(C'\fB is now rejected.\fR Any value other than \f(CW\*(C`less\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`greater\*(C'\fR previously fell through to the two-sided branch and returned a two-sided result mislabelled with the bad string, so a typo like \f(CW\*(C`alternative => "twosided"\*(C'\fR silently \*(L"worked\*(R". It now croaks unless \f(CW\*(C`alternative\*(C'\fR is one of \f(CW\*(C`two.sided\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`less\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`greater\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBZero/negative variance is guarded.\fR When every observation is tied the approximation's variance collapses to 0 and the old code divided by \f(CWsqrt(0)\fR: \f(CW\*(C`wilcox_test([5,5,5], [5,5,5])\*(C'\fR returned \f(CW\*(C`p = 0\*(C'\fR (a \*(L"significant\*(R" difference between identical samples). It now warns and returns \f(CW\*(C`p = 1\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBTwo-sided continuity correction at \f(CB\*(C`z = 0\*(C'\fB.\fR R uses \f(CW\*(C`sign(z) * 0.5\*(C'\fR, so the correction is \f(CW0\fR when the statistic sits exactly on its mean; the old code used \f(CW\*(C`\-0.5\*(C'\fR. Example: \f(CW\*(C`wilcox_test([1,4], [2,3], exact => 0)\*(C'\fR changed from \f(CW\*(C`p = 0.698535\*(C'\fR to \f(CW\*(C`p = 1\*(C'\fR (matches R).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`exp\*(C'\fB no longer shadows libm.\fR The local \f(CW\*(C`exp\*(C'\fR accumulator (mean of the statistic) shadowed the C library \f(CW\*(C`exp()\*(C'\fR; renamed to \f(CW\*(C`mean_w\*(C'\fR (two-sample) and \f(CW\*(C`mean_v\*(C'\fR (signed-rank). No active miscompute, removed as a latent hazard.
.PP
Cosmetic
.IX Subsection "Cosmetic"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Collapsed a no-op ternary that assigned the same signed-rank exact method string on both branches; the \f(CW\*(C`method\*(C'\fR field is now simply \f(CW\*(C`Wilcoxon signed rank exact test\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Portability (exact signed-rank helper)
.IX Subsection "Portability (exact signed-rank helper)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`exact_psignrank\*(C'\fB no longer calls \f(CB\*(C`powl()\*(C'\fB.\fR The \f(CW\*(C`2^n\*(C'\fR normaliser is now built by exact repeated doubling, which has no long-double libm dependency. This fixes an \f(CW\*(C`Undefined symbol "powl"\*(C'\fR load failure reported by a \s-1CPAN\s0 smoker (FreeBSD, perl 5.20, \f(CW\*(C`nvtype=double\*(C'\fR) whose libm lacks the long-double math functions; the symbol resolved on glibc, which is why local builds passed. \f(CW\*(C`long double\*(C'\fR accumulation in the \s-1DP\s0 is retained — only the \f(CW\*(C`powl\*(C'\fR call was at fault.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`int\*(C'\fB → \f(CB\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fB\fR for \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`max_v\*(C'\fR, and the \s-1DP\s0 loop counters, which also removes a \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR\-to\-\f(CW\*(C`int\*(C'\fR narrowing at the call site. The \f(CW\*(C`floor()\*(C'\fR result (\f(CW\*(C`k\*(C'\fR) stays signed so its negative\-\f(CW\*(C`q\*(C'\fR sentinel still fires, and is cast to \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR only after the \f(CW\*(C`k < 0\*(C'\fR check.
.PP
Tests
.IX Subsection "Tests"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Added \f(CW\*(C`t/wilcox_test.t\*(C'\fR (flat, no subtests): R\-agreement cases, option handling (\f(CW\*(C`paired\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`correct\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`exact\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`mu\*(C'\fR, named/positional \f(CW\*(C`x\*(C'\fR/\f(CW\*(C`y\*(C'\fR, \s-1NA\s0 dropping), regressions for all four bug fixes, argument-error and \f(CW\*(C`alternative\*(C'\fR\-validation checks, output shape, and \f(CW\*(C`no_leaks_ok\*(C'\fR coverage of the two-sample, exact, and paired allocation paths.
.SS "0.15"
.IX Subsection "0.15"
\&\f(CW\*(C`view\*(C'\fR function added, similar to R's \f(CW\*(C`head\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR:
    filter => {
        'Testosterone, total (nmol/L)' => sub { defined \f(CW$_\fR },
    }
.PP
was broken by the change in undefined variables in 0.14, but is back to being \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`col2col\*(C'\fR improvement in sectioning in \s-1README\s0
.PP
Numerous changes to prevent quadmath/long double \s-1CPAN\s0 test failures
.PP
Minimum Scalar::Util version in dist.ini is now 1.22, see https://www.cpantesters.org/cpan/report/6b682236\-6567\-11f1\-a3bc\-a055f9c4ba34
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`Digest::SHA\*(C'\fR is no longer needed, and removed as a dependency
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "read_table"
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBA comment-prefixed header is now read correctly.\fR \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR strips a
leading comment marker from the header line (so a file may begin with
\&\f(CW\*(C`#id,val\*(C'\fR), but that strip was dead code: the \s-1XS\s0 parser skipped \fIevery\fR line
beginning with the comment string before the callback ever saw it, so a
commented header was silently dropped and the first data row was mistaken for
the header. The parser now delivers the first content line even when it
begins with the comment marker, and only skips comment lines after the header
has been seen.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBCarriage returns inside quoted fields are preserved.\fR The parser stripped
\&\f(CW\*(C`\er\*(C'\fR unconditionally, so a quoted value such as \f(CW"x\ery"\fR lost its carriage
return and would not survive a \f(CW\*(C`write_table\*(C'\fR \-> \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR round-trip. \f(CW\*(C`\er\*(C'\fR
is now stripped only as part of a trailing \s-1CRLF\s0 line ending and as a stray \s-1CR\s0
\&\fIoutside\fR quotes; inside quotes it is literal data.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBDuplicate column names no longer corrupt \f(CB\*(C`hoa\*(C'\fB output.\fR With
\&\f(CW\*(C`output.type => \*(Aqhoa\*(Aq\*(C'\fR, a repeated column name pushed the same cell once per
occurrence, so the affected columns came out longer than the others and the
arrays no longer lined up by row. Columns are now keyed by unique header name
(first-seen order preserved, later values win, one warning emitted).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBA defined non-CODE callback is now an error.\fR Passing a defined argument
that was not a \s-1CODE\s0 reference silently fell through to slurp mode and ignored
the argument; it now croaks
(\fI\*(L"callback must be a \s-1CODE\s0 reference\*(R"\fR).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBAn undefined/empty \f(CB\*(C`hoh\*(C'\fB row-name now dies instead of keying on \f(CB""\fB.\fR
With \f(CW\*(C`output.type => \*(Aqhoh\*(Aq\*(C'\fR, a row whose row-name column was empty/undef was
stored under the \f(CW\*(Aq\*(Aq\fR key and raised \fI\*(L"uninitialized value\*(R"\fR warnings. It now
dies, naming the column and the offending data row.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBA numeric filter key past the last column now dies.\fR A 1\-based numeric
filter key greater than the column count was accepted, then silently extended
every row through the \f(CW$_\fR write-back. It is now rejected up front with a
message naming the column count.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`sep\*(C'\fB and \f(CB\*(C`delim\*(C'\fB together now die.\fR Supplying both silently preferred
\&\f(CW\*(C`delim\*(C'\fR; passing both is now an explicit error (\f(CW\*(C`delim\*(C'\fR remains an alias for
\&\f(CW\*(C`sep\*(C'\fR when used alone).
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBThe library no longer prints to \s-1STDOUT\s0.\fR The unknown-argument path used
\&\f(CW\*(C`say\*(C'\fR to dump the offending names to \s-1STDOUT\s0 before dying; the names are now
carried in the \f(CW\*(C`die\*(C'\fR message itself.
.PP
Better diagnostics
.IX Subsection "Better diagnostics"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Alignment errors now report \fBwhich data row\fR is ragged
(\fI\*(L"Alignment error on \s-1FILE\s0 data row N (X fields vs Y headers)\*(R"\fR), instead of
only the field/header counts.
.PP
Memory-leak fixes (exception paths)
.IX Subsection "Memory-leak fixes (exception paths)"
.PP
The parser allocated its working buffers (\f(CW\*(C`current_row\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`field\*(C'\fR, and — in
slurp mode — \f(CW\*(C`data\*(C'\fR) in the \s-1XS\s0 \f(CW\*(C`INIT:\*(C'\fR block, i.e. \fIbefore\fR any validation, and
freed them only by falling off the end of the function. Any non-local exit
therefore leaked:
.IP "\(bu" 4
the open-failure \f(CW\*(C`croak\*(C'\fR leaked the row buffer and field (and the slurp
accumulator);
.IP "\(bu" 4
far more commonly, a \f(CW\*(C`die\*(C'\fR thrown \fBinside the row callback\fR — which
\&\f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR does routinely on alignment errors, bad row names, and filter
exceptions — unwound straight out of the \s-1XS\s0 frame and leaked the field, the
current row, the line buffer, the slurp accumulator, \fIand the open file
handle\fR.
.PP
Allocations now happen in \f(CW\*(C`CODE:\*(C'\fR after every croak-able check, and every
long-lived resource (the file handle via \f(CW\*(C`SAVEDESTRUCTOR_X\*(C'\fR, the buffers via
\&\f(CW\*(C`SAVEFREESV\*(C'\fR) is tied to the save stack, which an exception unwinds. Measured
with \f(CW\*(C`Test::LeakTrace\*(C'\fR: a \f(CW\*(C`die\*(C'\fR mid-file went from 5 leaked SVs to 0, and an
open failure from 2 to 0. This is the likely source of the constant-size leaks
seen in CPAN-tester reports for the exception-path tests.
.PP
Performance
.IX Subsection "Performance"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB~2.5x faster parsing\fR (57 \-> 145 MB/s on a 100k\-row quoted file). The core
loop appended one character at a time with \f(CW\*(C`sv_catpvn(field, &ch, 1)\*(C'\fR; it now
scans runs of ordinary bytes with \f(CW\*(C`memchr\*(C'\fR / a bounded scan and appends each
run in a single \f(CW\*(C`sv_catpvn\*(C'\fR, copying field contents in bulk rather than byte
by byte.
.PP
Internal / non-behavioral
.IX Subsection "Internal / non-behavioral"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\s-1XS\s0 declarations moved from \f(CW\*(C`INIT:\*(C'\fR to \f(CW\*(C`PREINIT:\*(C'\fR; allocations deferred into
\&\f(CW\*(C`CODE:\*(C'\fR (see the leak fixes above).
.IP "\(bu" 4
The filter loop now aliases the row hash with \f(CW\*(C`local *_ = \e%line_hash\*(C'\fR
instead of copying it with \f(CW\*(C`local %_ = %line_hash\*(C'\fR. This removes a full
per-row hash copy for every filtered row and fixes a latent staleness bug:
after a filter mutated \f(CW$_\fR and the change was written back, \f(CW%_\fR still
reflected the pre-mutation copy, so a subsequent filter in the same row saw
stale values. With aliasing, \f(CW%_\fR \fIis\fR the row, so write-backs are always
visible.
.PP
Known limitation (not changed)
.IX Subsection "Known limitation (not changed)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`undef.val\*(C'\fB does not round-trip back to \f(CB\*(C`undef\*(C'\fB.\fR \f(CW\*(C`write_table\*(C'\fR renders an
\&\f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR cell as an empty field by default, and \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR maps an empty
field back to \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR, so the \fIdefault\fR round-trip is clean. But if a file is
written with a token such as \f(CW\*(Aqundef.val\*(Aq => \*(AqNA\*(Aq\fR, \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR has no
inverse option and reads \f(CW\*(C`NA\*(C'\fR back as the string \f(CW\*(AqNA\*(Aq\fR. \f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR also
cannot distinguish a deliberately quoted empty string (\f(CW""\fR) from a missing
value \*(-- both become \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR. Adding an \f(CW\*(C`na.strings\*(C'\fR\-style option to
\&\f(CW\*(C`read_table\*(C'\fR (mapping configurable tokens and/or empty fields to \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR)
would close this gap.
.PP
\fI\f(CI\*(C`write_table\*(C'\fI\fR
.IX Subsection "write_table"
.PP
Behavior change
.IX Subsection "Behavior change"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`undef\*(C'\fB cells now write as an empty field, not an empty string.\fR A missing
or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR value renders as nothing between separators (\f(CW\*(C`a,,c\*(C'\fR) rather than a
quoted empty string (\f(CW\*(C`a,\*(Aq\*(Aq,c\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`a,"",c\*(C'\fR). Supplying \f(CW\*(Aqundef.val\*(Aq => \*(AqNA\*(Aq\fR
(or any other token) still overrides this, exactly as before. This is the
only change that can alter the bytes of an existing output file; if you relied
on the previous default, pass \f(CW\*(Aqundef.val\*(Aq => \*(Aq\*(Aq\fR to keep an explicit empty
field, or your chosen placeholder.
.PP
Bug fixes
.IX Subsection "Bug fixes"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBWide-character / \s-1UTF\-8\s0 column names and row keys now round-trip.\fR
Previously, cells were looked up with the raw bytes of the column name
(\f(CW\*(C`hv_fetch(..., SvPV_nolen(name), strlen(name), ...)\*(C'\fR), which fails to match a
UTF\-8\-flagged hash key: the column header printed correctly but every cell
under it came back empty. All lookups now fetch by \s-1SV\s0 (\f(CW\*(C`hv_fetch_ent\*(C'\fR), header
lists are gathered and sorted as SVs (\f(CW\*(C`sortsv\*(C'\fR + \f(CW\*(C`sv_cmp\*(C'\fR, preserving the
flag) instead of being round-tripped through \f(CW\*(C`char *\*(C'\fR, and the \f(CW\*(C`row.names\*(C'\fR
column is matched with \f(CW\*(C`sv_eq\*(C'\fR rather than \f(CW\*(C`strcmp\*(C'\fR. Embedded \s-1NUL\s0 bytes in
keys are handled correctly as a side effect.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`col.names => []\*(C'\fB no longer loops forever.\fR An empty \f(CW\*(C`col.names\*(C'\fR array made
\&\f(CW\*(C`av_len()\*(C'\fR return \f(CW\*(C`\-1\*(C'\fR, which — compared against an unsigned \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR loop
index — wrapped to \f(CW\*(C`SIZE_MAX\*(C'\fR and ran effectively without end. This was fixed
for flat hashes previously; it was still present for hash-of-hashes,
hash-of-arrays, and array-of-hashes, plus both \f(CW\*(C`row.names\*(C'\fR header-filtering
loops. All such loops now use a signed index.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBTables wider than 65,535 columns no longer hang.\fR One header loop used an
\&\f(CW\*(C`unsigned short\*(C'\fR index that silently wrapped past 65,535 and never terminated.
It now uses \f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR like the rest of the code.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fBFlat-hash cells holding a reference now croak.\fR Every other input shape
rejects a nested reference with
\&\fI\*(L"Cannot write nested reference types to table\*(R"\fR; a flat hash instead
stringified it (e.g. \f(CW\*(C`ARRAY(0x55...)\*(C'\fR) into the file. It now croaks
consistently.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\fB\f(CB\*(C`\*(Aqundef.val\*(Aq => undef\*(C'\fB is handled cleanly.\fR It previously called
\&\f(CW\*(C`SvPV_nolen\*(C'\fR on \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR, raising an \fI\*(L"uninitialized value\*(R"\fR warning and
yielding an empty string by accident. It is now treated explicitly as an empty
field, with no warning.
.PP
Memory-leak fixes (exception paths)
.IX Subsection "Memory-leak fixes (exception paths)"
.IP "\(bu" 4
The row-key list gathered for hash-of-hashes input was leaked when the output
file could not be opened.
.IP "\(bu" 4
The \fI\*(L"Could not get headers\*(R"\fR croak on hash-of-arrays input leaked both the
already-open filehandle and the headers array.
.PP
Internal / non-behavioral
.IX Subsection "Internal / non-behavioral"
.IP "\(bu" 4
Numeric row labels are now formatted into a reused stack buffer instead of a
per-row \f(CW\*(C`savepv()\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`safefree()\*(C'\fR allocation (no functional change; removes a
cast\-away\-\f(CW\*(C`const\*(C'\fR and one allocation per row).
.IP "\(bu" 4
Several signed/unsigned index types were made consistent (\f(CW\*(C`SSize_t\*(C'\fR vs
\&\f(CW\*(C`size_t\*(C'\fR) to match \f(CW\*(C`av_len()\*(C'\fR and silence the conditions behind the loop bugs
above.
.PP
Tests
.IX Subsection "Tests"
.IP "\(bu" 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`t/write_table.t\*(C'\fR expanded from 17 to 69 assertions. New coverage targets each
fix above: the empty-field default and \f(CW\*(C`undef.val => undef\*(C'\fR (no warning),
\&\f(CW\*(C`col.names => []\*(C'\fR termination across all four input shapes, the
 >65,535\-column header loop (gated behind \f(CW\*(C`EXTENDED_TESTING=1\*(C'\fR), in-sequence
numeric row labels, nested-reference rejection, \s-1CSV\s0 quoting corners
(carriage return, separators inside column names, multi-character separators),
empty input writing no file, and \s-1UTF\-8\s0 column names and row keys. Two leak
assertions cover the exception paths above.
